@author "Didier Levet"
@remark "$VER: VLab_pss Guide 1.0 (26. octobre 2002)"
@remark "Created with GoldED 5.0 (27.7.0)"

@node MAIN "Welcome"

    VLab.pss 1.8 (27/10/2002)
    © 2002 Didier Levet, kakace@wanadoo.fr


    VLab.pss is a plugin for ArtEffect which allows you to capture video
    pictures using a VLab Classic or VLab Y/C frame grabber. The monitoring
    capability of the plug-in provides a preview of the incoming video
    signal in color or greyscale mode, and react in real-time to any setting
    changes, including gamma correction, brightness and contrast.

    @{"Requirements" link REQUIREMENTS}
    @{"Installation and usage" link USAGE}
    @{"Bugs and caveats" link BUGS}
    @{"Support and disclaimer" link SUPPORT}

    Congratulations to TH2A and "lolo". Their beloved plugin is finished :)

@endnode
@node REQUIREMENTS "Requirements"

    In order to operate, you need :
    - A VLab frame grabber (either Classic or Y/C).
    - ArtEffect 2.x or later.
    - CyberGraphX or Picasso96 RTG system.
    - AmigaOS 3.x

@endnode

@node USAGE "Installation and usage"

    To install the plugin, copy "vlab.pss" to the "ArtEffect:plugins2"
    directory. It will be available the next time you start ArtEffect,
    providing that a VLab can be detected.
    If all went fine, a new entry named "VLab..." shall appear in the
    "Project" menu. Pick this entry to open a large window showing various
    settings.

    @{fg shine}Input@{fg text}

    Input  : Select one of the inputs available on the VLab (either 2 or 3).
    Source : Select one of the video standard.
    Hue    : Hue correction (NTSC only). Useless for PAL signal.

    @{fg shine}Luminance filters@{fg text}

    VTR        : Enable Video Tape Recorder time base correction.
    Pre-Filter : Enable the chroma pre-filter.
    B&W source : Disable chroma filtering for B&W sources. The chroma
                 information adds noise to the luma signal, so don't
                 disable that filter for color input signals.
    Bandpass   : Select the centre frequency of the bandpass filter.
                 This filter removes the high luminance frequencies.
    Coring     : Level of noise reduction (coring threshold). This filter
                 removes low amplitude noise.
    K factor   : Aperture correction factor. If set to OFF, disable
                 the bandpass and coring filters. Otherwise, determines
                 the strength of these filters.

    @{fg shine}Image@{fg text}

    HiRes      : Select the High Resolution mode (upto 720 pixels per line).
    Lace       : Select the dual field per frame mode (Lace mode).
    Color      : Color/greyscale switch.
    Gamma      : Gamma correction.
    Brightness : Brightness correction.
    Contrast   : Contrast correction.

    @{fg shine}Clipping@{fg text}

    Those four gadgets select the image position and dimension for the next
    capture. The maximum values as well as the minimum steps are defined by
    the current image resolution (HiRes, Lace).

    @{fg shine}Monitoring@{fg text}

    Disable PiP   : If checked, disable the use of PiP/Video layer (whenever
                    available).
    Color preview : Color/greyscale switch.
    Preview       : Preview resolution.
    Start monitor : Open the monitoring window.

    @{fg shine}Misc@{fg text}

    Reset settings : Reset input-specific settings to their last saved
                     values.
    << GRAB >>     : Scan a new picture then display it into a new paint
                     window. The plugin's GUI remains opened, so you can
                     scan several pictures. Note that the image scanned is
                     not the one currently displayed in the monitoring
                     window. This button really causes a new capture to be
                     made.

    The plugin maintains the filters, image and clipping settings (as well
    as the source and hue selections) for each available input. When you
    change the video input, the settings of that input are used.

    Most settings changes apply in real time to the monitoring window. Thus
    you can see what the grab will look like.

    All settings are automatically saved upon exit, including the monitoring
    window position.

@endnode

@node BUGS "Bugs and caveats"

    This plugin has been tested with a VLab Y/C, Picasso96 RTG system, a
    PicassoIV graphics board and ArtEffect 4.0.

    The frame grabber is driven internally by custom code derived from the
    original vlab.library. This is a bit tricky, but I had no other choice
    since the vlab.library lacks a lot of features (such as color monitoring,
    luminance filters, etc).

    Although it's intended to support the VLab Classic frame grabber (which
    has only 2 CVBS inputs), I cannot make sure it works as expected because
    the internal implementation of this frame grabber is quite different.

    When running ArtEffect on a Hi-Color screen (15 or 16 bits), the PiP
    monitoring window is twice as large as expected because of a bug in
    Picasso96 v2.x

    Some troubles have been reported concerning the Video Layer (monitoring).
    To work around what could be a bug in some version of CyberGraphX, you
    can disable the use of the video layer for the monitoring (Disable PiP
    checkbox).

    ArtEffect manages plugin's settings by itself and stores configuration
    files in the "ArtEffect:settings" directory. If you have some troubles
    with the specific settings of the plugin, just delete the "VLab.cfg"
    file within this directory. It will be created anew the next time you
    run the plugin.

@endnode

